│ stop({"edit_points": [[1576, 1579, "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineMulDivRem.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe issue is that InstCombine is incorrectly transforming a       │
│ vector udiv operation into zeroinitializer (all zeros) when it shouldn't. The specific case involves a select instruction as the divisor where one lane can be zero (causing undefined behavior/poison) and    │
│ another lane is non-zero.\n\nIn the test case:\n- Dividend: <i32 42, i32 -7> (where -7 is 4294967289 as unsigned)\n- Divisor: select %x, <i32 -1, i32 -1>, <i32 0, i32 1>\n\nWhen %x = <true, false>, we       │
│ get:\n- Lane 0: 42 udiv -1 = 42 udiv 4294967295 = 0\n- Lane 1: -7 udiv 1 = 4294967289 udiv 1 = 4294967289\n\nBut InstCombine transforms this to <0, 0>, which is incorrect for lane 1.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s │
│ Log:\n\nThe log shows that `visitUDiv` calls `simplifyUDivInst` which returns `zeroinitializer`. This suggests that the simplification logic is incorrectly assuming that the entire vector division results   │
│ in zero.\n\nLooking at the InstCombineMulDivRem.cpp code, there's a transformation at lines 1576-1579:\n\n```cpp\n// Op0 / C where C is large (negative) --> zext (Op0 >= C)\n// TODO: Could use               │
│ isKnownNegative() to handle non-constant values.\nType *Ty = I.getType();\nif (match(Op1, m_Negative())) {\n  Value *Cmp = Builder.CreateICmpUGE(Op0, Op1);\n  return CastInst::CreateZExtOrBitCast(Cmp,       │
│ Ty);\n}\n```\n\nThis transformation assumes that if the divisor is negative (which as an unsigned value means it's large), then the result is the zext of (Op0 >= Op1). However, this logic is being applied   │
│ to vector types where only some lanes might be negative/large.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe root cause is that the pattern matching `match(Op1, m_Negative())` succeeds for vector types when all         │
│ elements are negative. In our case, the select produces <i32 -1, i32 1> when %x = <true, false>. However, the `m_Negative()` matcher likely checks if the value is known to be negative, and for a select      │
│ between a negative vector and a mixed vector, it might conservatively assume the result could be negative.\n\nBut more critically, even if the matcher correctly identifies that the divisor contains negative │
│ values, the transformation `zext (Op0 >= Op1)` is not equivalent to the original udiv when the divisor also contains small positive values (like 1 in our case).\n\nThe issue is that this transformation was  │
│ designed for scalar operations or cases where the entire divisor is guaranteed to be negative, but it's being incorrectly applied to vector operations where only some lanes are negative.\n\n4. Proposed Edit │
│ Point(s):\n\nThe problematic transformation at lines 1576-1579 in InstCombineMulDivRem.cpp needs to be restricted to not apply to vector types, or to only apply when all lanes of the divisor are known to be │
│ negative.\n\nHowever, looking more carefully at the reproducer, the actual issue might be different. Let me reconsider:\n\nThe select produces either <-1, -1> or <0, 1>. When it produces <0, 1>, lane 0 has  │
│ division by zero (undefined/poison), and lane 1 has division by 1.\n\nThe simplification should not assume that the entire result is zero. The current logic in simplifyUDivInst is likely folding this        │
│ incorrectly.\n\nActually, looking at the debug output again, the transformation happens in visitUDiv calling simplifyUDivInst, which returns zeroinitializer. This suggests the issue is in                    │
│ InstructionSimplify.cpp, not in the InstCombine-specific transformation.\n\nBut wait, the opt log shows \"IC: Replacing %div = udiv ... with <2 x i32> zeroinitializer\" right after visiting the udiv         │
│ instruction, and the backtrace points to visitUDiv line 1547, which is the simplifyUDivInst call.\n\nThe real issue is in the simplifyDivRem function in InstructionSimplify.cpp. At lines 1102-1109, it       │
│ checks if any element of a constant divisor vector is zero, but our divisor is not constant - it's a select.\n\nHowever, there's another issue: the transformation at lines 1576-1579 in                       │
│ InstCombineMulDivRem.cpp. The `m_Negative()` matcher when applied to our select instruction might be returning true because one of the possible values (<-1, -1>) is negative, but the other possible value    │
│ (<0, 1>) is not entirely negative.\n\nGiven the complexity, the safest fix is to disable the negative divisor optimization for vector types, since the reasoning doesn't hold for vectors where lanes can have │
│ different properties.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nThe fix restricts the negative divisor optimization to scalar types only, preventing incorrect transformations on vector udiv operations where some lanes might not │
│ follow the same pattern as others."})                                                                                                                                                                          │
